What is wrong with this C++ code that is supposed to implement a linked list class with a constructor and a destructor? 

The code has several problems: 
1. It does not use the proper syntax for a constructor. The constructor should have the following form: 

    LinkedList::LinkedList(int arr[], int n) 
    : head(new Node), head->data(arr[0]), head->next(NULL) 
    for (int i = 1; i < n; i++) 
    { 
        Node* temp = new Node; 
        temp->data = arr[i]; 
        temp->next = NULL; 
        head->next = temp; 
        head = temp; 
    } 

2. It does not allocate memory for the head variable. It should be declared as a pointer to a Node object and assigned the address of a newly created Node object. 
3. It does not delete the Node objects that have been created. This must be done by using the delete operator. 
4. It does not properly set the next field of the Node object. It should be set to point to the next Node object in the list. 
5. It does not check for null when dereferencing the head variable. 
